{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"11237d93-3abd-4f60-9273-eb22cf7b9182","content":"Here's how to set up **NuGet Trusted Publishing** with OIDC — no API keys stored anywhere:\n\n## 1. Configure nuget.org\n\n1. Sign in to [nuget.org](https://www.nuget.org) → **Manage Packages**\n2. Select your package (or reserve the ID under **Upload** if it's new)\n3. Go to **Trusted Publishers** → **Add** → **GitHub Actions**\n4. Fill in:\n   - **Owner**: `myorg`\n   - **Repository**: `mylib`\n   - **Workflow**: `publish.yml`\n   - **Environment**: `nuget` *(recommended — adds a manual approval gate)*\n\n## 2. Create a GitHub Environment\n\nIn your repo → **Settings** → **Environments** → **New environment** → name it `nuget`. Optionally add required reviewers for release approval.\n\n## 3. Add the workflow\n\nCreate `.github/workflows/publish.yml`:\n\n```yaml\nname: Publish to NuGet\n\non:\n  push:\n    tags: [\"v*\"]          # trigger on version tags like v1.0.0\n\njobs:\n  publish:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    environment: nuget                  # must match nuget.org config\n    permissions:\n      id-token: write                   # required for OIDC token\n      contents: read\n\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n\n      - uses: actions/setup-dotnet@v4\n        with:\n          dotnet-version: '8.0.x'\n\n      - run: dotnet pack src/MyLib/MyLib.csproj -c Release -o ./artifacts\n\n      - name: Push to NuGet\n        run: dotnet nuget push ./artifacts/*.nupkg\n          --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n> **No `--api-key` needed** — the OIDC token from `id-token: write` is presented automatically and nuget.org validates it against your trusted publisher config.\n\n## 4. Publish\n\n```bash\ngit tag v1.0.0\ngit push origin v1.0.0\n```\n\n**Key benefits**: No secrets to rotate, scoped to a specific repo/workflow/environment, and the optional environment gate gives you manual approval before any publish.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"982a63a1-dab3-4429-bb8b-d577e62fe90a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to set up secure NuGet publishing from GitHub Actions using trusted publishing (without API keys). This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. Let me provide a concise answer.\n\nThe modern approach is to use NuGet's trusted publishing with OIDC tokens, which was introduced in 2023-2024. This avoids storing API keys as secrets.\n\nLet me outline the steps:\n\n1. Register the package on nuget.org and configure trusted publishing (GitHub Actions OIDC)\n2. Create a GitHub Actions workflow that uses OIDC to authenticate\n\n\n3. On nuget.org, you'll link your GitHub repository as a trusted publisher by specifying your organization, repository, and optionally the workflow or environment\n4. In your workflow, you'll use the OIDC token that GitHub Actions provides to authenticate with NuGet without needing to store an API key\n\nActually, I'm second-guessing the exact implementation details here—let me think through what's actually well-supported and straightforward for this use case. Now I'm going to write out a practical GitHub Actions workflow that demonstrates how to authenticate with nuget.org using the OIDC token and push the package.","outputTokens":1326},"id":"8df579b1-2363-470d-95e7-f280e403052a","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:37:09.518Z","parentId":"6ea4b5da-11c0-483a-9617-c14c6a0ddbde"}
